	Mesh = {Animals; Brain; Brain Mapping; Drosophila; Female; Fruit; Male; Mushroom Bodies; Odors; Olfactory Pathways; Olfactory Receptor Neurons; Pheromones; Presynaptic Terminals; Sex Characteristics; Smell; Synapses},
	Month = {Mar},
	Mynote = {{During the single cell labelling studies initiated in Jefferis, Marin et al. (2001), we noticed almost immediately that projection neurons whose dendrites innervated the same glomerulus (therefore receiving identical olfactory information) had highly reproducible axon branching patterns in higher centres. I demonstrated that a statistical classifier could reliably identify neurons by their axons alone -- a key result in our next paper (Marin, Jefferis et al., 2002) that was published together with similar work from Richard Axel's group (Wong, Wang and Axel, Cell, 2002). However neither of these studies could allow direct co-visualisation of neurons: combining genetic labelling of single cells into a 3D atlas struck me as an important technique for the future. During a short post-doc at Stanford, I started a collaboration with Torsten Rohlfing of the neurosurgery department, who had been developing software for 3D registration of human fMRI samples. After almost 2.5 years of data analysis and the generation of further experimental data, we published a comprehensive map of input to higher olfactory centres, that showed evidence of organisation by biological value.}},
