	Journal-Full = {Current biology : CB},
	Keywords = {Independent, Independent},
	Mesh = {Animals; Brain; Drosophila Proteins; Drosophila melanogaster; Female; Genotype; Male; Nerve Tissue Proteins; Neurons; Sex Characteristics; Sexual Behavior, Animal; Transcription Factors},
	Month = {Sep},
	Mynote = {{This study and the companion paper (Yu et al, for which I performed computational analysis and technical supervision) substantially revised the view on the extent of sexual dimorphism in the fly brain. We identified sex differences in coarse brain anatomy so robust that they can 100\% reliably identify the sex of a brain. At the level of neural circuits, earlier studies had proposed that behavioural differences arise from altered brain activity not brain wiring. However, we identified 19 new sexually dimorphic neuronal classes in the central brain, to add to three previously reported. Previous work emphasised male-specific neurons that might selectively release behaviours encoded in circuits that were sexually largely isomorphic. However our results included many cases of neurons present in both sexes but showing anatomical differences that we predicted to reroute information flow.}},
